metadata.name: Averno #66
metadata.description:
The work sits at the intersection of atmospheric abstraction and symbolic representation,
where generative aesthetics become a vehicle for an exploration of the perceptual threshold between form and dissolution.
Vertical structures, resembling slender shrubs or nervous filaments, construct a visual lattice that oscillates between transparency and density, suggesting a synthetic vegetation suspended between nature and algorithm.

The composition stands out for its use of digital color, with gradients that simulate traditional techniques such as pastel or watercolor, while maintaining a coherence typical of code. The generative intervention is not merely ornamental: it is a formal strategy that translates the indeterminacy of the landscape into an autonomous aesthetic language.

The sinuous shapes that emerge from below and rise upwards are not mere presences: they suggest a humanity in the making‚Äîor rather, an anthropomorphic echo generated by the system, a tension between organic mark-making and computational logic.

metadata.name: Bloomside of The Past Field #158
metadata.description:
Made this work as a part of trying to make misprint effects, while maintaining the square form.
The scene are the flowers and other vegetations. Sometimes the scene will have the rain, snow and other weathers.

I imagined the scene was a form of painting, drawing or pictures on the postcard. So, all of them will have been signed as a loved sign, dusted sign (the spiders will come) and left unsigned. 

-----

my friends are married and getting married. I was left and I'm growing the flowers for myself in the sideline of the park, house, or elsewhere.

metadata.name: Coronado #101
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

Please see fxtext article linked from main project page for more background on the project and rendering notes.

Some key commands in live mode:

G : Toggle grain
S : Save current resolution
1 : 4000x5000
2 : 6000x7500
3 : 8000x10000
4 : 10000x12500
5 : 12000x15000
6 : 14000x17500
(1-6 work best on Chrome)
(rendering takes longer as resolution increases)

metadata.name: CA Panico RGB #11
metadata.description:
Another tribute to Stephen Wolfram and his cellular automata, that's a reworking of my previous CA Panico collection.

In this version the RGB basic colors reign supreme, every single color is set by a cellular automata formula, giving life to interesting and particular textures and patterns.

Press 'S' to download.

metadata.name: CA Panico #79
metadata.description:
Third chapter of the trilogy dedicated to Stephen Wolfram's cellular automata.
 
Compared to CA Vista and CA Monti, CA Panico aims to further abstract the concept of landscape using CA rules in a more massive way.

The great variety of CA rules that controls the coloring and textures, noise influence, division into quadrants, chance of having glitches and outages all combined with 25 palettes and 5 different formats means that the outputs will be very varied and peculiar.

Press 'S' to download, you can zoom downloaded output to enjoy all the details.

metadata.name: CONNECT D-ajop1j021 #19
metadata.description:
‚ÄªDue to the characteristics of the work, the output will vary depending on the screen size.
If the screen size is the same, the output will be the same.
Thumbnail images are 800px x 800px.

First, the base color is placed, then random symbols (letters) are placed in a draw() loop process.
Then, specific symbol are linked to each other by their x,y color.

Red, Blue, Yellow, and Black colors are references to the untitled print work by Hiroshi Kawano, and works by Mondrian. I started this work by imitating and looking at their work.

This work is the beginning of my exploration of the relationship between weaving, computers, and generation, and I plan to produce the CONNECT series using similar techniques.

Please feel free to contact me if you have any inquiries.

Artwork by hasaqui, @hasaqui.
Made with p5js

metadata.name: Snake Memories #7
metadata.description:
A zero-player game that transforms the mechanics of Snake into mark-making. Each generation grows, hunts, and eventually dies, leaving it's form on the canvas. The piece is an infinite generative animation with minimalist sound.

Built with p5.js.
